  <div class="case-hero">
    <div class="case-number">Project 06</div>
    <h1 class="case-title">Geospatial ETL &amp;<br><span>Geodatabase Automation</span></h1>
    <p class="case-summary">
      Designing and automating the data infrastructure that keeps a multi-project GIS
      environment consistent — from geodatabase schema design and CAD-to-GIS transformation
      standards, to Python and FME pipelines that synchronize datasets across disciplines
      without manual intervention.
    </p>
    <div class="case-meta">
      <div class="meta-item"><span class="meta-label">Domain</span><span class="meta-value">Data Engineering</span></div>
      <div class="meta-item"><span class="meta-label">Stack</span><span class="meta-value">Python / FME / ModelBuilder</span></div>
      <div class="meta-item"><span class="meta-label">Role</span><span class="meta-value">GIS Specialist</span></div>
      <div class="meta-item"><span class="meta-label">Scope</span><span class="meta-value">Organization-wide</span></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="case-content">

    <div class="phase">
      <div class="phase-label-col"><div class="phase-num">00</div><div class="phase-name">Context</div></div>
      <div class="phase-body">
        <p>A GIS environment supporting multiple concurrent projects across different disciplines —
        environmental, engineering, infrastructure — generates data from many sources:
        <strong>CAD design files</strong> from engineers, field surveys, provincial datasets,
        and project-specific geodatabases maintained by different teams.</p>
        <p>Without consistent standards and automated synchronization, this data fragments quickly —
        leading to duplicate features, broken joins, incompatible projections, and reporting
        outputs that can't be trusted without manual reconciliation before every delivery.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="phase">
      <div class="phase-label-col"><div class="phase-num">01</div><div class="phase-name">Problem</div></div>
      <div class="phase-body">
        <p>Three interconnected problems drove this work — each compounding the others:</p>
        <div class="callout">
          <strong>Data integrity chain</strong>
          (1) CAD files from engineering disciplines had no defined transformation standard into GIS —
          each conversion was ad hoc, producing inconsistent geometry and attributes.<br><br>
          (2) Multi-source datasets updated on different schedules were being manually re-synced
          before every report cycle — slow, error-prone, and undocumented.<br><br>
          (3) No organization-wide geodatabase schema existed — feature class naming, domain values,
          and subtype structures varied across projects, making cross-project queries unreliable.
        </div>
        <p>The cumulative effect was that significant analyst time was spent on data
        <em>reconciliation</em> rather than data <em>analysis</em> — a structural problem
        that wouldn't be solved by working harder, only by building better systems.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="phase">
      <div class="phase-label-col"><div class="phase-num">02</div><div class="phase-name">Approach</div></div>
      <div class="phase-body">

        <div class="phase-subtitle">Geodatabase Schema Design</div>
        <div class="phase-divider"></div>
        <p>An organization-wide <strong>geodatabase schema</strong> was designed from scratch —
        defining feature class structures, <strong>domains and subtypes</strong> to constrain
        attribute values, standardized field naming conventions, and version control procedures.
        The schema was documented and adopted as the baseline for all new projects.</p>

        <div class="phase-subtitle">CAD-to-GIS Transformation Standards</div>
        <div class="phase-divider"></div>
        <p>A formal <strong>CAD-to-GIS transformation workflow</strong> was developed to handle
        incoming engineering design files — defining layer mapping rules, coordinate system
        transformation parameters, geometry cleaning steps, and attribute population logic.
        This replaced ad hoc conversions with a repeatable, auditable process that preserved
        spatial accuracy and produced GIS-ready feature classes directly usable in analysis.</p>

        <div class="phase-subtitle">ETL Pipeline Automation</div>
        <div class="phase-divider"></div>
        <p>Geospatial ETL pipelines were built using <strong>Python and ArcGIS ModelBuilder</strong>
        to automate dataset synchronization across sources — pulling updates from provincial
        data feeds, engineering deliverables, and field collection systems, applying
        transformation logic, and loading into the target geodatabase with metadata intact.
        <strong>FME</strong> was used for more complex multi-format translations requiring
        conditional logic and cross-platform data alignment.</p>

        <div class="tech-stack">
          <span class="tech-pill">Python</span>
          <span class="tech-pill">ArcPy</span>
          <span class="tech-pill">FME</span>
          <span class="tech-pill">ModelBuilder</span>
          <span class="tech-pill">Geodatabase Schema Design</span>
          <span class="tech-pill">Domains / Subtypes</span>
          <span class="tech-pill">CAD-to-GIS Transformation</span>
          <span class="tech-pill">Version Control</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="phase">
      <div class="phase-label-col"><div class="phase-num">03</div><div class="phase-name">Outcome</div></div>
      <div class="phase-body">
        <div class="outcome-stats">
          <div class="outcome-stat"><div class="outcome-value">↓</div><div class="outcome-label">Manual reconciliation eliminated</div></div>
          <div class="outcome-stat"><div class="outcome-value">Org</div><div class="outcome-label">-wide schema adopted</div></div>
          <div class="outcome-stat"><div class="outcome-value">↑</div><div class="outcome-label">Cross-project data reliability</div></div>
        </div>
        <p>The geodatabase schema became the single structural standard across all projects —
        enabling cross-project queries, consistent reporting outputs, and onboarding of
        new datasets without custom transformation work each time.</p>
        <p>The CAD transformation standard eliminated the most common source of geometry
        errors in the GIS environment — broken features from inconsistent layer mapping
        and missed coordinate system conversions from engineering deliverables.</p>
        <div class="callout">
          <strong>Systems thinking over task execution</strong>
          The real value of this work wasn't any single pipeline — it was shifting the
          GIS environment from a reactive, per-project setup to a proactive, standards-driven
          infrastructure. Each new project plugged into existing schemas and pipelines
          rather than rebuilding from scratch.
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

  </div>

